  "prompt": "How is Earth's axis tilt measured?",
  "response": "Earth's axial tilt, also known as obliquity, is measured using precise astronomical observations and calculations. Here are the key methods:\n\n1. Astronomical Observations\n- Tracking the angle between Earth's rotational axis and its orbital plane\n- Measuring the maximum angular distance of the Sun from the celestial equator\n- Using telescopes and precise positional measurements\n\n2. Laser Ranging Techniques\n- Using laser measurements from satellites\n- Tracking precise Earth rotation and orientation\n- Providing extremely accurate angle measurements\n\n3. Modern Measurement Techniques\n- Very Long Baseline Interferometry (VLBI)\n- Satellite-based geodetic measurements\n- Precise GPS and space-based tracking systems\n\n4. Current Measurement\n- The current axial tilt is approximately 23.4 degrees\n- This angle changes slightly over long time periods due to gravitational interactions\n\n5. Historical Tracking\n- Ancient astronomers like Hipparchus first estimated the tilt\n- Modern techniques allow much more precise measurements\n\nThese methods combine to provide accurate, ongoing measurements of Earth's axial tilt with high precision, helping scientists understand long-term planetary dynamics and climate variations.",
